===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|drogge||medicine|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|frm}} {{term|drogue||cure, pharmaceutical product|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|drogue|lang=fro}}, {{term|drocque||tincture, pharmaceutical product|lang=fro}}, of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from {{etyl|dum}} or {{etyl|gml}} {{term|droge|lang=dum}}, as in {{term|droge|lang=dum}} {{term|vate||dry vats, dry barrels|lang=dum}}, mistaking {{term|droge|lang=dum}} for the contents, which were wontedly dried herbs, plants or wares. ''Droge'' comes from [[Middle Dutch]] {{term|droghe|drōghe|dry|lang=dum}}, from {{etyl|osx}} {{term|drogi|drōgi|dry|lang=osx}}, from {{proto|Germanic|draugijaz|dry|lang=en}}. Cognate with English {{term|dry}}, German {{term|trocken||dry|lang=de}}. See also {{l|nl|droog}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{pharmacology}} A [[substance]] used to treat an [[illness]], relieve a [[symptom]], or modify a [[chemical]] [[process]] in the [[body]] for a specific purpose.
#: ''Aspirin is a '''drug''' that reduces pain, acts against inflammation and lowers body temperature.''
#: ''The revenues from both brand-name '''drugs''' and generic '''drugs''' have increased.''
# {{pharmacology}} A substance, often [[addictive]], which affects the [[central nervous system]].
# A chemical or substance, not necessarily for [[medical]] purposes, which alters the way the [[mind]] or body works.
# A substance, especially one which is [[illegal]], [[ingest]]ed for [[recreational]] use.
#* '''1971''', [[w:Hunter S. Thompson|Hunter S. Thompson]], ''Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas'', Harper Perennial 2005 edition, p. 3,
#*: We were somewhere around Barstow on the edge of the desert when the '''drugs''' began to take hold.

